	"notes": [
		{
			"id": "nCakMcP6CYL85-U66",
			"markdown": "Traders are merchants, financiers, brokers, logisticians, smugglers, and dealmakers who move wealth, goods, and influence through society. Whether you are a corporate executive managing interstellar trade routes, a caravan master crossing radioactive wastelands, a black-market fixer operating out of a neon-lit megacity, a free captain hauling speculative cargo between frontier colonies, or a quartermaster keeping an army supplied during wartime, you survive by understanding people, markets, and systems of exchange. In cyberpunk settings, Traders may be criminal middlemen, syndicate negotiators, cyberware brokers, or information dealers. In space opera and frontier campaigns, they are often merchant captains, cargo operators, procurement officers, financiers, diplomats, or independent shipping magnates. Whatever form they take, Traders are the people who keep resources moving and know how to profit from opportunity long before anyone else realizes it exists.\n\nYour primary role is economic, social, and logistical influence. A Trader is far more than someone who buys and sells goods: you understand how wealth, supply chains, contracts, favors, and institutions shape the world around you. Many Traders specialize in negotiation, shipping, finance, procurement, market speculation, or political influence, developing expertise in skills such as Merchant, Finance, Accounting, Administration, Freight Handling, Law, Market Analysis, Shiphandling, Diplomacy, or Fast-Talk. Even away from the negotiating table, you remain valuable by organizing expeditions, arranging transportation, securing supplies, managing crews, cultivating contacts, navigating bureaucracy, and finding opportunities others overlook. Whether you are a polished executive, a frontier merchant surviving on razor-thin margins, a military logistics officer, or a smuggler living one step ahead of customs inspectors and organized crime, the group depends on you whenever money, influence, transportation, or supplies become critical to success.\n\nThe *Broker* specializes in negotiation, investment, influence, and market manipulation. Corporate executives, trade consortium representatives, financial speculators, contract negotiators, and business magnates all fit this archetype. You thrive in boardrooms, diplomatic functions, exclusive clubs, and high-stakes negotiations where fortunes can change hands in a single conversation. Your skills likely emphasize Merchant, Finance, Accounting, Diplomacy, Politics, Administration, and social influence. The constant pressure to accumulate wealth and maintain influence often leads to disadvantages such as Greed, Overconfidence, Miserliness, Jealousy, or Code of Honor (Professional).\n\nThe *Free Trader* survives by moving cargo, passengers, and information through dangerous or unstable regions. Independent freighter captains, caravan operators, frontier merchants, and long-haul transport specialists all belong to this archetype. In space campaigns, you may command a tramp freighter operating far from major authorities; in grittier settings, you might run convoys through gang territory or transport contraband between isolated communities. Your skills commonly focus on Freight Handling, Navigation, Shiphandling, Spacer, Merchant, and practical logistics. Years spent gambling fortunes against distance, danger, and uncertainty frequently result in disadvantages such as Compulsive Carousing, Code of Honor (Pirate’s), Cowardice, Chummy, or Overconfidence.\n\nThe *Quartermaster* specializes in procurement, logistics, organization, and large-scale operational support. Military supply officers, expedition coordinators, shipping managers, colony administrators, and corporate operations specialists all fit this role. You understand how to move personnel, fuel, weapons, food, medicine, and equipment through hostile environments without letting the system collapse. While others focus on glory or exploration, you make certain everyone has ammunition, transportation, spare parts, and functioning infrastructure. Your skills typically emphasize Administration, Accounting, Freight Handling, Leadership, Law, Merchant, and organizational planning. The burdens of responsibility and bureaucracy often encourage disadvantages such as Workaholic, Honesty, Sense of Duty, Stubbornness, or Miserliness.\n\nThe *Smuggler* operates in the shadows of legitimate commerce, moving illegal goods, restricted technology, fugitives, or sensitive information past authorities and criminal rivals alike. Some Smugglers are charming rogues and independent operators; others are hardened criminals tied to powerful syndicates or revolutionary movements. You survive through deception, improvisation, and knowing which laws can be bent — and which people can be bribed. Your skills often focus on Streetwise, Forgery, Navigation, Merchant, Fast-Talk, Shiphandling, and social manipulation. Constant danger, unstable alliances, and life outside the law commonly produce disadvantages such as Greed, Trickster, Secret, Overconfidence, Curious, or Bad Temper."
		}
	]
}
